{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"13124eeb-a28e-4756-b5ab-6d5a101ea2c6","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Lifecycle flow:**\n\n| Transition | Event |\n|---|---|\n| App launches | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closing | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n| iOS/Mac background | `Backgrounding` (save state via `e.State`) |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/macOS only and gives you a `BackgroundingEventArgs.State` dictionary to persist transient data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"93bfc6e2-2bf3-4d95-81c1-dc6a99898cc2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"A421:30E8DC:5F427A6:67B6212:69F00513"},"id":"55895ba5-cbe5-410a-bb29-e0fba41725fc","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:53:47.983Z","parentId":"50674d2b-f7e1-48f4-be9f-14060280412b"}
